SUMMARY:
<summary>
A 2025 market commentary critiques China Merchants Bank's (CMB) 2024 performance, highlighting rapid asset growth alongside significant regulatory penalties and potential risk management issues. Key points include: CMB's total assets grew 10.19% to over 12.15 trillion yuan, but its provision coverage ratio dropped sharply by 25.72 percentage points to 411.98%. The bank received 78 regulatory fines totaling over 27 million yuan, ranking sixth among joint-stock banks. Major fines were for loan misappropriation (e.g., a 4.9 million yuan penalty at Zhengzhou branch), wealth management violations (a 12 million yuan fine for CMB and its subsidiary), and improper insurance sales. Despite a slight 0.47% revenue dip, net profit grew 1.22% to 148.391 billion yuan, though the article questions if this growth is sustainable given fine costs and a narrowing net interest margin to 2.02%.
